  <static seed="289" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddingFractionsOfInches10.pg">
    <statement><p>A <m>2\times4</m> piece of lumber in your garage is <m>{40{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}}</m> inches long. A second <m>2\times4</m> is <m>{34{\textstyle\frac{9}{16}}}</m> inches long. If you lay them end to end, what will the total length be?</p>
<p>The total length will be <fillin characters="7" name="AnSwEr0001"/> inches.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>74{\textstyle\frac{23}{32}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find the total length in inches, we add the two lengths together.</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
    {40{\textstyle\frac{5}{32}}}+{34{\textstyle\frac{9}{16}}} \amp  = 40+\frac{5}{32}+34+\frac{9}{16}\\
                \amp  = 74+\frac{5}{32}+\frac{9}{16}\\
                \amp  = 74+{{\frac{23}{32}}}\\
                \amp  = {74{\textstyle\frac{23}{32}}}
\end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>So the total length is <m>{74{\textstyle\frac{23}{32}}}</m> inches.</p>
</solution>
